  "Prerequisites": "A basic familiarity with clinical workflows and a general awareness of how digital tools are used in healthcare settings is all that is needed to get started with this course.",
  "Learning objectives": "By the end of this course, you will be able to identify the key causes of automation bias in clinical settings and explain how over-reliance on AI-generated outputs can lead to diagnostic and treatment errors. You will also apply practical strategies to critically evaluate AI recommendations, helping you maintain safe, patient-centred care in your everyday practice.",
  "lessons": [
    {
      "lesson title": "Automation Bias in Healthcare",
      "order": 1,
      "Description": "This lesson introduces the concept of automation bias and explains why it is particularly relevant in healthcare settings where clinicians increasingly work alongside AI-powered decision support tools. You will explore how and why healthcare professionals can place excessive trust in automated outputs, sometimes overriding their own clinical judgement even when the AI may be wrong. Through straightforward examples, the lesson highlights the types of errors that can occur when automation bias goes unchecked, and the potential impact on patient safety. By the end of this lesson, you will have a clearer understanding of the psychological factors that contribute to automation bias and why awareness of this tendency is an essential first step in using AI tools responsibly in clinical practice.",
      "status": "draft",
      "content": "Why clinicians may over-trust AI outputs, and how errors happen.",
